This is the second story (afaik) in which Genk tried to come up with a granularity, a gradation in the amount of scumbaggery revealed. The intention is a valid one, but it is met with the fact that the scale is viewed the wrong way around. 
It is recognized that sexual assault is a crime. It is accepted that the worst offenders (Ailes, Weinstein...) deserve jail time. My point is that, when sexual assault/misconduct is brought up those worst offenders are the point of reference, the metric to which all other instance is compared to. 
This leads to impossible conclusions. When Harvey is your point of reference, a cat-caller will be put in the same bag ; the immediate comment comes to "this dude's an asshole too". When the highest level of predation is the standard meter, any lesser offence will be retroactively compounded to that meter. 
If the aforementioned cat-caller is the entry level breach of conduct, there is no upper limit. When the perp is at least deserving of public shaming, the gradation can apply. The comment becomes : "this guy's worse", and this is the the whole point.
It takes nothing from the importance and gravity of any level of the acts, doesn't deny any victim's suffering. 
It has an effect on victims too, this one bag fits all viewpoint. If all predators are classified the same, their victims are too, no matter what has been inflicted upon them. 
The healing process is different for the victim of a serial groper like Bush than for the victim who spent years servicing her/his tormentor, as it is different for the victim that needs reconstructive surgery as a starting point of the process.
In conclusion, those acts, as reprehensible as they are, can and should be characterized and put on a spectrum starting with the lowest level and going up.
